        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">37. Albany St. | Regent’s Park. | N. W.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Oct 4.</date>
                    <salute>Dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Darwin,</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>Thanks for patronizing my efforts. I will not rest till I have obtained what you want to know in Re Otter dogs<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>See “Land &amp; Water” Saturday<ref target="#foot.f3"/>   Pray make use of me—<hi rend="underline">in any way</hi></p>
<p>I am so very sorry to hear that you are still unwell   I trust you will soon be better.</p>
<p>I cant help smiling at the fightings &amp; disputes between your disciples &amp; your non disciples at the British Association.<ref target="#foot.f4"/></p>
<p>Did you ever see a pack of hounds fighting for a bone, when the huntsman’s back is turned. Just so our friends attack &amp; defend your theories thrown down into the middle of them.</p>
<p>Please throw us down <hi rend="underline">another</hi> bone to fight about, the old bone is nearly picked clean now—</p>
<p>Yours ever | Frank Buckland</p> 
                </div>
            </div>

            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to CD’s query in <hi rend="italic">Land and Water</hi> about otter-hounds (see n. 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">See <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5227F.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter to F. T. Buckland, 2 October 1866</ref> and nn. 4–6.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s query on otter-hounds appeared in the 6 October 1866 issue of <hi rend="italic">Land and Water</hi>, p. 244 (see letter to <hi rend="italic">Land and Water</hi>, [2 October 1866]).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">Buckland is referring to the recent meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science held in Nottingham from 22 to 30 August 1866 (<hi rend="italic">Athenæum</hi>, 11 August 1866, p. 161). In his presidential address, <ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_2007.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">William Robert Grove</ref> had mentioned CD’s works among others in natural history that were supportive of transmutation of species rather than successive creations (<ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_3166.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">W. R. Grove 1866</ref>). Buckland attended the meeting and presented papers (see <hi rend="italic">Report of the thirty-sixth meeting of the British Association for the Advancement of Science held at Nottingham</hi>, pp. 70–1). For more on the reception of Grove’s address, see the <ref target="./DCP-LETT-5234.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Charles Pritchard, 8 October 1866</ref> and nn. 3 and 4.</note>
        </div>        
            
